\chapter{Adjoints.}

\section{Adjuncitons.}

Let $J$ be an indexing category (simply, any category which we will use to 
index things), $\cc$ a category, and suppose that 
each functor $F: J \to \cc$ has a limit $\Lim F$ in $\cc$. Then what 
we can do with this is 
define the functor $\Lim: \cc^J \to \cc$ where the functor sends 
functor $F: J \to \cc$ to their limits:
\[
    F: J \to C \mapsto  \Lim F.
\]
Why is this functorial? Well, suppose $\theta: F \to G$ is a morphism (natural 
transformation) between two functors $F, G: J \to \cc$ in $\cc^J$. 
Recall that $\Delta: \cc \to \cc^J$ is the diagonal functor.
Then, as limits, 
they have natural transformations 
\[
    \epsilon_F: \Delta(\Lim F) \to F \qquad \epsilon_G: \Delta(\Lim G) \to G
\] 
which are equipped with the universal property expressed in the 
diagrams below.
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \Delta(\Lim F) \arrow[r, "\epsilon_F"] 
        &
        F\\
        \arrow[u, dashed, "u"]
        \Delta(C)\arrow[ur, swap, "f"]
    \end{tikzcd}
    \hspace{1cm}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \Delta(\Lim G) \arrow[r, "\epsilon_G"] 
        &
        G\\
        \arrow[u, dashed, "v"]
        \Delta(D)\arrow[ur, swap, "g"]
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
where $C, D$ are objects of $\cc$ and $f, g$ are morphisms in $\cc^J$. 
Then observe that we can connect these diagrams: 
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \Delta(\Lim G) 
        \arrow[r, "v"]
        &
        G\\
        \Delta(\Lim F)
        \arrow[u, dashed, "h"]
        \arrow[ur, swap, "\theta \circ \epsilon_F"]
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
which forces the unique existence of a morphism (natural transformation) 
$h: \Delta(\Lim F) \to \Delta(\Lim G)$ in $\cc^J$. If we set $F(\theta) = h$, 
then we see that this behavior is functorial. The other trivial properties are simple to check. 

\textcolor{NavyBlue}{So, what's the big deal about the limit $\Lim $of a functor actually being a secret 
functor whenever all limits are admitted?}

First, the fact that it is a functor means we have a truly remarkable relationship between 
the functors 
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \cc^J \arrow[r, shift right = 0.5ex, swap, "\Lim "] 
        &
        \cc 
        \arrow[l, shift left = -0.5ex, swap, "\Delta"]
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}

Now to really see the significance, let's reinterpret what it means for a functor $F: J \to \cc$ to 
have a limit in $\cc$. It means that the diagram below 
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \Delta(\Lim F) \arrow[r, "\epsilon_F"] 
        &
        F\\
        \arrow[u, dashed, "u"]
        \Delta(C)\arrow[ur, swap, "f"]
        &
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
commutes. Specifically, whenever we have a morphism $f: \Delta(C) \to F$ in $\cc^J$, there 
exists a unique morphism $u: C \to \Lim F$. 
This is old news. However, an equivalent way to interpret this result is to observe 
that it also is communicating to us a bijection
\begin{statement}{ProcessBlue!10}
    \begin{equation}\label{lim_delta_adjoints}
       \hom_{\cc^J}(\Delta(C), F) \cong \hom_{\cc}(C, \Lim F).
    \end{equation}
\end{statement}
which is given by some bijection $\phi_{C, F}$. Moreover, this bijection is actually natural in
each object, but we won't worry about that for now. The point here is that we call 
the above relation between functors, equipped with the above natural bijection, an
\textbf{adjunction}.
\\

The above result can be applied for 
all kinds of limits; and the beauty of it is that it captures the individual philosophy 
of each individual limit. 
For example, when $J$ is discrete, the limit 
becomes a product. Specifically, our functors reduce to the relation 
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \prod_{j \in J}\cc \arrow[r, shift right = 0.5ex, swap, "P"] 
        &
        \cc 
        \arrow[l, shift left = -0.5ex, swap, "\Delta"]
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
where $\prod_{j \in J}\cc$ is product category, and
we define $P$ to act on the product category as
\[
    (A_j)_{j \in J} \mapsto \prod_{i \in J}A_i
    \quad 
\]  
(hence, $P$ for "product")
where $(A_j)_{j \in J}$ denotes a "tuple" of elements,
and the diagonal functor behaves as
\[
    A \mapsto (A_j)_{j \in J} \text{ where } A_j = A \text{ for  all j}.
\]
Then from our previous work we automatically get the natural bijection 
between hom-sets
\[
    \hom_{\prod_{j \in J}\cc}\Big((A)_{j \in J}, (C_j)_{j \in J}\Big) 
    \cong 
    \hom_{\cc}\left(A, \prod_{j \in J} C_j\right).
\]
The above bijection actually makes a lot of sense; it says that if you have a family of morphisms 
into the factors $(C_j)_{j \in J}$ of a product $\prod_{j \in J} C_j$, 
then you get a unique morphism into the product of those factors, 
which is \emph{exactly} the universal property of products! 

As another example, suppose $J$ is the category
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}
        1
        \arrow[r, shift right = 0.5ex, swap, "g"]
        \arrow[r, shift left = 0.5ex, "f"]
        &
        2
    \end{tikzcd}.
\end{center}
Then the limit of a functor $F: J \to \cc$ (when it exists) is an equalizer
of the morphisms $f' = F(f)$ and $g' = G(f)$. 
The diagram below expresses the universal property.
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
        \text{Eq}(f', g') 
        \arrow[r, "e"]
        &
        F(1)
        \arrow[r, shift right = 0.5ex, swap, "g'"]
        \arrow[r, shift left = 0.5ex, "f'"]
        &
        F(2)\\
        C \arrow[u, dashed, "u"]
        \arrow[ur, swap, "h"]
    \end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
where $f' \circ e = g' \circ e$ and  $f' \circ h = g' \circ h$. 
Now because 
\[
    \hom_{\cc^{J}}(\Delta(C), F)
    = 
    \{ h: C \to F(1) \mid f' \circ h = g' \circ h  \}
\]
we see that
relation \ref{lim_delta_adjoints} gives us 
\[
    \hom_{\cc^{J}}(\Delta(C), F) = \{ h: C \to F(1) \mid f' \circ h = g' \circ h  \} 
    \cong \hom_{\cc}(C, \text{Eq}(f',g')).
\]
This is just a different way of stating the exact concept of an equalizer!

The general formula we produced cleverly
offers clarity of limits from a different perspective, one which we wouldn't normally 
envision ourselves (a fact that Saunder Mac Lane believes as to why it took so long for adjoints to be 
defined). 

Adjunctions, which are beautiful correspondences between pairs of functors such at $\Lim$ and $\Delta$
are abundant in math, and we now define them generally.

