\begin{definition}
    Let $\cc$ and $\dd$ be categories. We say an \textbf{adjunction}
    $(F, G,\phi)$ is a pair of functors 
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            \cc \arrow[r, shift left=0.6ex,"F"] & \dd 
            \arrow[l,shift right =-0.6ex, "G"]
        \end{tikzcd}
    \end{center}
    and a bijection $\phi_{C,D}$ which assigns each pair of objects
    $C, D$ a bijection of sets
    \[
        \phi(C, D) \mapsto \phi_{C, D}: \hom_\dd(F(C), D) \cong \hom_\cc(C, 
        G(D))
    \]  
    which is natural in both $C$ and $D$. In this case, we say that
    $F$ is the \textbf{left-adjoint} and $G$ is the
    \textbf{right-adjoint}. 
\end{definition}
    
    Now, what do we mean by the above equation being natural in both
    $C$ and $D$? Well, for all $h: C' \to
    C$ and $k: D \to D'$, we must have that 
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            \hom_\dd(F(C), D)\arrow[r, "\phi_{C,D}"]
            \arrow[d, swap, "k_*"]
            &
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D))\arrow[d, "G(k)_*"]\\
            \hom_\dd(F(C),D') \arrow[r, "\phi_{C,D'}"]
            &
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D'))
        \end{tikzcd}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            \hom_\dd(F(C), D)\arrow[r, "\phi_{C,D}"]
            \arrow[d, swap, "(F(h))^*"]
            &
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D))\arrow[d, "h^*"]\\
            \hom_\dd(F(C'),D) \arrow[r, "\phi_{C,D'}"]
            &
            \hom_\cc(C', G(D))
        \end{tikzcd}
    \end{center}
    all commute. Here, recall that $k_*(f: F(C) \to D) = k \circ f$,
    and $h^*(g: C \to G(D)) = g \circ h$. The
    commutativity of the diagrams can be written our in terms of
    equations; if $f: F(C) \to D$, then
    \begin{align}
        \phi(k \circ f) = G(k) \circ \phi(f)\\
        \phi(f \circ F(h)) = \phi(f) \circ h.
    \end{align}
    Since $\phi$ is a bijection, we know that 
    \[
        \phi^{-1}: \hom_{\cc}(C, G(D)) \to \hom_\dd(F(C), D)   
    \]
    exists and is also a bijection. And because $\phi$ is natural in
    $C$ and $D$, we know that $\phi^{-1}$ also preserves naturality as
    well. Thus we also have that 
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D))\arrow[r, "\phi^{-1}_{C,D}"]
            \arrow[d, swap, "G(k)_*"]
            &
            \hom_\dd(F(C), D)\arrow[d,  "k_*"]\\
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D')) \arrow[r, "\phi^{-1}_{C,D'}"]
            &
            \hom_\dd(F(C),D')
        \end{tikzcd}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            \hom_\cc(C, G(D))\arrow[d, swap, "h^*"]
            \arrow[r, "\phi^{-1}_{C,D}"]
            &
            \hom_\dd(F(C), D) \arrow[d, "(F(h))^*"]\\
            \hom_\cc(C', G(D)) \arrow[r, "\phi^{-1}_{C,D'}"]
            &
            \hom_\dd(F(C'),D)
        \end{tikzcd}
    \end{center}
    commutes. We can also express this commutativity in terms of
    equations betwee morphisms. If $g: C \to G(D)$, then
    \begin{align}
        k \circ \phi^{-1}(g) = \phi^{-1}(G(k) \circ g)\\
        \phi^{-1}(g) \circ F(h) = \phi^{-1}(g \circ h). 
    \end{align}
    What we're seeing here is the adjunctions give us \textit{a lot of
    shit}, but not bad shit; it gives a lot of good shit. As we'll
    see, there's even more to explore. 


    \section*{Universality from $C$ to $G$.}
    It turns out that the concept of an adjunction goes much deeper
    than what we've just outlined here. Not only do adjunctions appear
    in many places, but they also give rise to universal morphisms. To
    see this, let $D = F(C)$. Then $\phi_{F(C), F(C)}$ forms a
    bijection between the sets 
    \[
        \hom_\cc(F(C), F(C)) \cong \hom_\dd(C, G(F(C))).
    \]
    Now let's chase the identity $1_{F(C)}: F(C) \to F(C)$. 
    The function $\phi$ sends
    $1_{F(C)}$ to a unnique morphism $\phi(1_{F(C)}): C \to G(F(C))$. Call
    this $\eta_C$. 

    For any other $f': F(C) \to F(C)$, we can use equation (3) to
    observe that 
    \begin{align*}
        \phi(f') = \phi(f' \circ 1_{F(C)}) &= G(f') \circ \phi(1_{F(C)})\\
        &= G(f') \circ \eta_C.
    \end{align*}
    Look familiar? Recall Proposition 3.2! The isomorphism 
    \[
        \phi: \hom_\cc(F(C), F(C)) \cong \hom_\dd(C, G(F(C)))
    \]
    which sends each $f': F(C) \to F(C)$ to $G(f') \circ \eta_x$ holds
    if and only if $\eta_C: C \to G(F(C))$ is a universal morphism
    from $C$ to $G$. \textcolor{NavyBlue}{Hence, we see that for
    \textit{every object} $C$ of $\cc$, an adjunction gives rise to a
    universal morphism from $C$ to $G: \dd \to \cc$!}

    Thus there exists some function $\psi$ where 
    \[  
        C \longmapsto \eta_C : C \to G(F(C))
    \]
    which makes $\psi$ a natural transformation, so that 
    \[
        \psi: I_C \to G\circ F
    \] 
    where $I_C$ is
    the trivial functor on $\cc$. Now consider again $h: C' \to C$,
    and observe by equation (4), 
    \begin{align*}
        G(F(h)) \circ \eta_{C'} = G(F(h)) \circ \phi(1_{C'})
        &= \phi(F(h) \circ 1_{C'})\\
        &= \phi(1_{C'} \circ F(h))\\
        &= \phi(1_{C'}) \circ h\\
        &= \eta_{C'} \circ h.
    \end{align*}
    where in the second step used equation (3), and in the fourth step
    we used equation (4). This gives rise to the diagram
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
            C' \arrow[r, "\eta_{C'}"]
            \arrow[d, swap, "h"]
            &
            G(F(C')) \arrow[d, "G(F(h))"]\\
            C \arrow[r, swap, "\eta_{C}"]
            &
            G(F(C))
        \end{tikzcd}
    \end{center}
    which commutes. This then shows that the function which sends $C
    \to \eta_C$ is natural in $C$. That is, not only do we have a
    correspondence between objects of $\cc$ and universal arrows from
    $C$ to $G$, this correspondence respects naturality! 

    \section*{Universality from $F$ to $D$.} 
    We can also perform the same procedure we just did using equations
    (3) and (4) on the equations (5) and (6). Thus consider the
    inverse $\phi^{-1}: \hom_{\cc}(C, G(D)) \to \hom_\dd(F(C), D)$. 
    Suppose we set $C = G(D)$. Then $\phi^{-1}$ gives the bijection 
    \[
        \hom_\dd(F(G(D)), D) \cong \hom_{\cc}(G(D), G(D)).
    \]
    As before, let's consider $1_{G(D)}: G(D) \to G(D)$. Suppose we
    write 
    \[
        \epsilon_D = \phi^{-1}(G(D)): F(G(D)) \to D.   
    \]
    Now consider any $g: G(D) \to G(D)$. Then 
    \begin{align*}
        \phi^{-1}(g) = \phi^{-1}(1_{G(D)} \circ g)
        &= \phi^{-1}(1_{G(D)}) \circ F(g)\\
        &= \epsilon_D \circ F(g).
    \end{align*}
    where we used equation (6). 
    As this is the action of $\phi^{-1}$, and because $\phi^{-1}$
    establishes the above isomorphim between the hom-sets, we can use
    the dual version of Proposition 3.2 (check yourself, it works) to
    conclude that $\epsilon_D:F(G(D)) \to D$ is a universal arrow from $F$
    to $D$, for every object $D$ of $\dd$. Moreover, we can conclude that 
    $\epsilon: F\circ G \to I_\dd$
    is a natural transformation, where $I_\dd$ is the identity functor
    on $\dd$. 

    Finally, observe that 
    \[
        1_{G(D)} = \phi(\phi^{-1}(1_{G(D)})) = \phi(\epsilon_D) = G
        (\epsilon_D) \circ 
        \eta_{G(D)}
    \]
    and that 
    \[
        1_{F(C)} = \phi(\phi^{-1}(1_{F(C)})) = \phi^{-1}(\eta_C) = \epsilon_
        {F(C)} \circ F(\eta_C).
    \]
    Hence we see that the composite natural transformations
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzcd}
        G \arrow[r, "\eta_{G}"] & G \circ F \circ G
        \arrow[r,"G(\epsilon)"] & G
        \end{tikzcd}
        \hspace{0.5cm}
        \begin{tikzcd}
        F \arrow[r, "F(\eta)"] & F \circ G \circ G
        \arrow[r, "\epsilon_{F}"]
        & 
        F
        \end{tikzcd}
    \end{center}
    are both the identity. As we now have a notion of $\eta$ and
    $\epsilon$, we denote $\eta$ as the \textbf{unit} and $\epsilon$
    as the \textbf{counit}. Now all of our analysis proves the following
    theorem. 
    \begin{thm}
        $(F, G, \phi)$ forms an adjunction between $\cc$
        and $\dd$ if and only if
        \begin{description}
            \item[$\bm{(i)}$]There exists a natural transformation
            $\eta: I_\cc \to G \circ F$ such that 
            for each object $C$ of $\cc$, the
            morphism 
            \[
                \eta_C: C \to G(F(C))
            \]
            is universal from $C$ to $G$, and if $f: F(C) \to D$
            \[
                \phi(f) = G(f) \circ \eta_C.  
            \]
            \item[$\bm{(ii)}$] There exists a natural transformation
            $\epsilon: F \circ G \to I_\dd$ such that for each object
            $D$ of $\dd$, the morphism
            \[
                \epsilon_D: F(G(D)) \to D  
            \]
            is universal from $F$ to $D$, and if $g: C \to G(D)$,
            \[
                \phi^{-1}(g) = \epsilon_{D} \circ F(g).
            \]
        \end{description}
    \end{thm}

