        equivalent. Hence we see that $\textbf{eval}$ is actually a
        counit $\epsilon_A: P_Y(E^Y(A)) \to A$. Since such a counit
        exists for each $A$, this gives rise to an adjunction, so that
        $E^Y$ is right adjoint to $P_Y$ for every object $Y$ in $\cc$.
    \end{prf}

    Finally, we have everything we need to move onto to the main point
    of this section. 

    \begin{definition}
        Let $\cc$ be a category. We say $\cc$ is a \textbf{cartesian closed 
        category} if the functors 
        \[
            U: \textbf{C} \to \textbf{1} 
            \qquad
            \Delta: \cc \to \cc  \times \cc 
            \qquad 
            P_Y = (-)\times Y: \cc \to \cc
        \]
        have right adjoints. In other words, $\cc$ is 
        \textbf{cartesian closed} if 
        \begin{itemize}
            \item[1.] There exists a terminal object $T$ 
            \item[2.] $\cc$ has finite products 
            \item[3.] An exponential object $A^Y$ for every $A \in
            \cc$ for all $Y$.   
        \end{itemize}
    \end{definition}

    Thus the work we just did was used in showing that our
    three-bullet point list is another definition of a cartesian
    closed category. Often, only one definition or the other is
    offered, and it's not trivial how they're equivalent, so it can be
    confusing. Thus our work shows that either definition is
    equivalent. 

    Some examples include \textbf{Set}, which we already dealt with.
    \textbf{Set} has a terminal object (empty set), has finite
    products, and has an exponential object. More interesting is
    \textbf{Cat}, which is catesian closed. In this case, \textbf{1}
    is the terminal object, \textbf{Cat} is closed under finite
    products, and the exponential object exists. In this case,
    $\cc^{\bb}$ is simply the functor category! 

    \textcolor{MidnightBlue}{At first, it seemed silly to define
    $\cc^\bb$ as the category of functors \textit{from} $\bb$ to
    $\cc$, since it seemed that it ought to be denoted $\bb^\cc$.
    However, we see that this was really just because of the concept
    of exponentials, which isn't known when being introduced functor
    categories.}
    
    \begin{exercise}[Exercise 4.6.1]
        \begin{enumerate}
            \item \textcolor{purple}{If 
            $U$ is any set, show that the preorder
            $\mathcal{P}(U)$ of all subsets of $U$ is a cartesian 
            closed category.}

            \item \textcolor{purple}{
            Show that any Boolean algebra, regarded as a
            preorder, is cartesian closed.}
        \end{enumerate}
        \vspace{-0.8cm}
    \end{exercise}

    \begin{solution}
        \begin{enumerate}
            \item To show that $\mathcal{P}(U)$ is cartesian closed, 
            we simply check the criteria. First, $\mathcal{P}(U)$ contains 
            a terminal object; since every $X \in \mathcal{P}(U)$ is a
            subset of $U$, we have that there exists a unique 
            morphism $t_X: X \to U$. 

            In addition, we have finite products. Let $A, B$ be two
            elements of $\mathcal{P}(U)$. Then if $D \le A$ and $D \le
            B$, we have that $D \le A \cap B$. Hence the following
            diagram commutes. 
            \begin{center}
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
                    & \arrow[dl, swap, "f"] D \arrow[d, dashed, "h"]
                    \arrow[dr, "g"]& \\
                    A & \arrow[l, "i"] A \cap B \arrow[r, swap, "j"] & B 
                \end{tikzcd}
            \end{center}
            Hence we see  that $\cap$ is actually a product in our 
            preorder! Since we may take finite intersections in 
            $\mathcal{P}(U)$, we have finite "products".
            
            Finally, observe that the left diagram 
            \begin{center}
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
                    A & A^Y \times Y \arrow[l, swap,
                    "{\textbf{eval}_A}"]\\
                    & X \times Y \arrow[ul, "g"] 
                    \arrow[u, swap, dashed, "{(h, \text{id}_Y)}"]
                \end{tikzcd}
                \hspace{1cm}
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
                    A & A^Y \cap Y \arrow[l, swap,
                    "i"]\\
                    & X \cap Y \arrow[ul, "g"] 
                    \arrow[u, swap, dashed, "h"]
                \end{tikzcd}
            \end{center}
            becomes the diagram on the right in this category. Here 
            we denote $i$ has the inclusion.
            Now
            suppose that $g: X \cap Y \to A$, meaning that $X \cap Y \le A$.
            Then $X \le A$, so  that there exists 
            a morphism $h: X \to A^Y = X \to A$. Hence we get the
            diagram 
            \begin{center}
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
                    A & A \cap Y \arrow[l, swap,
                    "i"]\\
                    & X \cap Y \arrow[ul, "g"] 
                    \arrow[u, swap, dashed, "h"]
                \end{tikzcd}
                \hspace{1cm}
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = 1.4cm, row sep = 1.4cm]
                    A \\
                    X \arrow[u, "h"]
                \end{tikzcd}
            \end{center}
            and from this perspective, we see that $A^Y = A$. Hence
            exponentials trivially exist in our preorder. 

            Since $\mathcal{P}(U)$ contains a terminal object, finite
            products, and exponential objects, we have that any
            preorder $\mathcal{P}(U)$ is cartesian closed. 

            Obviously wrong, so what's the exponential?
        \end{enumerate}
    \end{solution}